> If this dish were a place, it would be a sunny little fishing village somewhere on the coast of Sardinia. If it were a time, it would be an al fresco lunch, on a sun-dappled terrace, with a cold bottle of rosé. For this recipe we combined simple, light, fresh flavours to create a nostalgia-inducing meal that will leave you plenty of time to get online and book your next holiday. Daydreams included as standard.

Boil a #large pot{} of water. Peel and finely chop both the @onion{1}(peeled and finely chopped) and the @garlic cloves{4}(peeled and finely chopped). Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(finely chopped). Chop the @sun-dried tomatoes{50%g}(chopped) and finely chop the @green chilli{1}(finely chopped). Slice the @tiger prawns{250%g} in half lengthways.

Heat a good glug of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot cook your onion, garlic and sun-dried tomatoes. Sprinkle in as much chilli as you dare together with a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Cook for ~{5%minutes} and be careful not to let your veggies burn.

Add the @chopped tomatoes{2%12oz cans} and let the mixture bubble away on medium-low heat for around ~{10%minutes} until you have a nice thick sauce.

Cook the @wheat spaghetti{250%g} in the boiling water with a pinch of @salt{} for around ~{11%minutes}. Once your pasta is 'al dente', drain it.

> 'Al dente' means it is cooked but there is just a hint of firmness left in the middle.

Once your sauce has thickened, stir in the tiger prawns and cook them for a few mins until they turn pink.

Next, drop your pasta into the frying pan with your sauce. Sprinkle over your parsley, then toss the ingredients together to mix them.

> If you don't fancy redecorating the kitchen, then you can always give it a good stir instead.

Serve and gobble immediately.